Civil disputes and claims 
     Estate law
     Easements/property line disputes
     Land use planning
     Real estate law 

Based in Lewiston, Browitt Law Office represents clients throughout Idaho and Washington but particularly the parts of those states located in the Inland Northwest. Browitt Law Office has created this website as a service to the Internet community and to provide information about the firm, its attorney and areas of practice.

The issue of water rights is as contentious as any in the Western United States, and this potential for conflict is surfacing with heightened frequency in the Inland Northwest. With an expanding population and an ever-increasing demand for this precious resource, all water users – be they irrigators, municipal providers or owners of a small domestic well – need to protect their interests. 

Jim Browitt is among the few attorneys in the region who focus on this complex legal realm. He is experienced in permitting/licensing matters, like Idaho’s ongoing stream adjudication processes, and firmly grasps the nuances of administrative measures, such as Washington’s Yakima Basin Integrated Water Resource Management Plan. Additionally, Jim is well-versed in water quality issues (discharge and dredge-fill permitting), shared well contracts, conjunctive (surface water-groundwater) management, and easements related to water use.

Jim’s knowledge in this field is greatly reinforced by his affiliation with Laura A. Schoeder, the charter member of Schroeder Law Offices, P.C., a firm that represents water-rights clients in five western states and consults internationally. Jim serves as Of Counsel  for Schroeder Law Offices, frequently representing the firm on matters it handles in Idaho and Washington. On occasion, Jim engages Laura as a consultant for Browitt Law Office. Jim is also a contributor to Schroeder Law Office’s widely read Water Law Blog. 



With overburdened courts often magnifying the length and cost of litigation, adverse parties are increasingly turning to alternative dispute resolution methods. Mediation is a process in which a trained facilitator, operating as a neutral third party, helps adversaries resolve their differences. Unlike a judge, the mediator facilitator does not render decisions; rather, he or she guides a process in which disparate stakeholders – be it two people or a roomful of involved individuals – collectively work toward crafting creative solutions. 

Jim Browitt received training from the Northwest Institute of Dispute Resolution as a civil mediator and as a mediator facilitating agreements in environmental and public policy disputes. In this capacity, he is associated with Patrick D. Costello, the principal of Cd’A ADR Conflict Management Services, which works with individuals and for public or private organizations throughout
the Inland Northwest.

Jim is a protégé of Pat Costello, a former professor and Idaho state magistrate, having learned from and worked closely with him as a third-year law student at the University of Idaho College of Law. As a legal intern in UI’s Legal Aid Clinic, Jim conducted numerous mediations under the direction of Prof. Costello and Prof. Maureen Laflin, the Director of Clinical Programs, and frequently co-mediated with both. His experience in this setting ranged from facilitating child custody and property settlements to participating in a federal court civil rights case, where he represented 13 civilly committed individuals who had been classified as sexually violent predators.
